The number has declined from last year's 21 in the same period, but the Western Cape Education Department is still concerned. CAPE TOWN At least 17 schools in the Western Cape were broken into and vandalised during the holidays.While the number has declined from last year's 21 in the same period, the Western Cape Education Department is still concerned. Between December and January, the department had hired additional security at schools identified as high risks.The department's Millicent Merton says most incidents could be described as minor, except for one. It is most unfortunate that Uitsig High School was once again vandalised. Security guards at the school were reportedly stoned and threatened with guns. As a result water pipes and electrical cables were damaged and/or stolen. It has put the school in a situation where it can t function. (Edited by Masechaba Sefularo)